programRuleActions.content: Postpone rubella vaccination if the child has received blood products in the last 3 months. If possible receiving blood products should be avoided for up to 2 weeks.
It is contraindicated to give the Rotavirus vaccine if the child is HIV+ and not on ART, and/or severely immuno-compromised or if there was a previous severe allergic reaction.
It is contraindicated to give the BCG vaccine, if the child is HIV+ and not on ART

Postpone the  measles vaccination until stabilized with ART treatment if the child is HIV+ and showing symptoms of severe immunosuppression,. It is contraindicated to give the measles vaccine if the child has had a previous severe allergic reaction to the vaccine.
" Be aware, it is advisable to defer vaccination until after an acute infection with temperature >39 degree C".
" If the child is HIV+ and showing symptoms of severe immuno-suppression, postpone vaccination until stabilized with ART treatment. "

It is Contraindicated to give the Measles vaccine, if the child has had a previous sereve allergic reaction to the vaccine
*WARNING* Measles supplement should only be given under certain conditions, such as measles outbreak. Check with your supervisor if there is no measles outbreak.

Vaccination providers should adhere as closely as possible to recommended vaccination schedule. Administration at recommended ages and in accordance with recommended intervals between doses of multi dose antigens provide optimal protection.
It is contraindicated to give the BCG vaccine, if the child is HIV+ and not on ART

At the beginning of the programme the average month at visit might increase as children get older but it should eventually plateau in a stable population as younger children would replace older ones who are leaving the programme. Independently from the stage of roll-out, the average age at enrollment should not variate much as the EPI has a relatively strict schedule based on the age of the child. The age might be higher at the beginning of the program as it might be trying to catch up on older children, but the age should then go steadily down though time as the program embeds in the health activities at PoC.
visualizations.title: Age in Months at Immunization Enrollment (Registration)

dataElements.name: EIR - Measles 0
dataElements.description:
Measles. 2 doses. 9-12 months and 15-18 months recommended schedule; 4 weeks minimum interval between doses. This vaccine is contraindicated after a severe allergic reaction (e.g. anaphylaxis) to a previous dose. If the child is showing symptoms of severe immunosuppression, postpone vaccination until stabilized with ART treatment.

SUPPLEMENTARY DOSE IF MEASLES OUTBREAK.

dataElements.name: EIR - RV 1 (Rota Teq)
dataElements.description: Rotavirus (Rota Teq) 3 dose. As early as 6 weeks; 4 weeks minimum interval between doses. Do not give if > 24 months old. Be aware, this vaccine should be postponed in case of ongoing acute gastroenteritis or fever with moderate to severe illness. Precautions are necessary if these is a history of intussusception or intestinal malformations, chronic gastrointestinal disease, and severe acute illness. Be aware, if the child is showing symptoms of severe immunosuppression, postpone vaccination until stabilized with ART treatment.

dataElements.name: EIR - Rubella 1
dataElements.description: Rubella. 1 dose. 9 or 12 months with containing measles vaccine. As a general rule, live vaccines should be given either simultaneously, or at least 4 weeks apart. Oral polio vaccine is the exception and can be given any time before or after RCA. Interference may occur between MMR and yellow fever vaccines if they are simultaneously administered to children < 2 years of age. If the child has received blood products <3 months, postpone vaccination. If possible receiving blood products should be avoided for up to 2 weeks post vaccination.
